Abstract.

In this note we prove existence of a solution to a system of Markovian BSDEs with interconnected obstacles. A key feature of our system, and the main novelty of this paper, is that we allow for the driver fisubscriptğ‘“ğ‘–f_{i} of the iğ‘–i-th component of the Yğ‘ŒY-process to depend on all components of the Zğ‘Z-process. This extends the existing theory on reflected BSDEs, which only addresses problems where fisubscriptğ‘“ğ‘–f_{i} depends on Zisuperscriptğ‘ğ‘–Z^{i}.

It is important to remark that a characterization as in (1.2) also holds in non-Markovian frameworks and we mention that switching problems often arise in economics, finance and power system management, amongst many other applied fields (see e.g. [2, 3, 4, 5, 7, 8, 10, 18, 19, 21, 22] and the references therein).

Problems like (1.1) have been studied at a theoretical level in the case when, for any i=1,â€¦,mğ‘–1â€¦ğ‘ši=1,...,m, the function fisubscriptğ‘“ğ‘–f_{i} depends only on the state variable zisuperscriptğ‘§ğ‘–z^{i} and possibly on (yi)iâˆˆÎ“subscriptsuperscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–ğ‘–Î“(y^{i})_{i\in\Gamma} (see, e.g., [6, 13]). In that setting existence (and uniqueness) results were provided (also for the non-Markovian case) by using comparison principles for solutions of BSDEs. Such comparisons do not hold in our framework since fisubscriptğ‘“ğ‘–f_{i} depends on (zi)iâˆˆÎ“subscriptsuperscriptğ‘§ğ‘–ğ‘–Î“(z^{i})_{i\in\Gamma}, hence we must rely on different methods.

The main objective of this paper is indeed to consider systems in which, for i=1,â€¦,mğ‘–1â€¦ğ‘ši=1,...,m, functions fisubscriptğ‘“ğ‘–f_{i} not only depend on the state variable ziâˆˆâ„dsuperscriptğ‘§ğ‘–superscriptâ„ğ‘‘z^{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{d} but on all components of the state variable z:=(zi)iâˆˆÎ“assignğ‘§subscriptsuperscriptğ‘§ğ‘–ğ‘–Î“z:=(z^{i})_{i\in\Gamma}. In particular we show that if Ïƒâ€‹ÏƒâŠ¤ğœsuperscriptğœtop\sigma\sigma^{\top} is bounded and uniformly elliptic, then (1.1) has a solution, provided that the switching costs (giâ€‹j)i,jâˆˆÎ“subscriptsubscriptğ‘”ğ‘–ğ‘—ğ‘–ğ‘—Î“(g_{ij})_{i,j\in\Gamma} are sufficiently regular. We adopt a usual penalization scheme (see (3.5) below) to handle the reflection constraints and rely deeply on essentially three facts: i) the representation of solutions of BSDEs as deterministic functions of tğ‘¡t and Xğ‘‹X; ii) smoothness of giâ€‹jsubscriptğ‘”ğ‘–ğ‘—g_{ij}, which enables fundamental bounds in the penalisation scheme; iii) existence of a transition density of Xst,xsubscriptsuperscriptğ‘‹ğ‘¡ğ‘¥ğ‘ X^{t,x}_{s} for any s>tğ‘ ğ‘¡s>t, which satisfies a so-called domination condition.

Our work is a first step towards the solution of (1.1) in general non-Markovian setup. The paper is organized as follows. In Section 2 we set out the notations and make standing assumptions that hold throughout the paper. In Section 3, we prove our existence result in a number of steps. First we introduce the penalization scheme associated with (1.1) and study its properties (in particular we show in Proposition 3.1 that the time derivative of the penalizing term is uniformly bounded). Then we use an argument based on weak convergence and the aforementioned domination condition (see also [12]) to obtain a convergent subsequence of solutions to the penalized problems. We finally show that the limit of such subsequence solves (1.1) and provide a representation of (Yi,Zi)iâˆˆÎ“subscriptsuperscriptğ‘Œğ‘–superscriptğ‘ğ‘–ğ‘–Î“(Y^{i},Z^{i})_{i\in\Gamma} as deterministic functions of (t,X)ğ‘¡ğ‘‹(t,X). We leave for future investigation questions of uniqueness of the solution and its links to optimal switching problems. The latter will inevitably feature a more general structure than (1.2).
